# Deploy (do the work in WSL — do not only tell the user)

**Primary product:** `monitoring-app-v2` — **standalone** replacement for `monitoring-app`; target **full functional parity** (see `monitoring-v2-standalone-parity.mdc`).

**Legacy:** `monitoring-app` (GAS). Prefer not to change it for **new product features** (use v2 + API) unless the user asks for legacy work — but when this session **does** change GAS files, **`clasp push` is part of the mandatory pipeline** (see above). **Do not remove or break APIs** the legacy app (or others) still use; extend backend routes for v2 instead.

**Azure DevOps:** For **alert**, **people-analytics-api**, and **monitoring-app-v2**, see **`azure-devops-push-only.mdc`**: the agent **`git commit`** on **`dev`**, then **`scripts/sync-changed-azure-repos.sh`** (syncs **all** changed product trees to Azure **`dev`**), then **`git push origin dev`** (not **`main`** unless the user said so). Subtree script is fallback only. **Do not** run `docker` / `kubectl` unless the user explicitly asks for a manual deploy.

When this session **changes** code **not** covered by those pipelines (or legacy flows), **run the full deploy pipeline yourself** in **Ubuntu WSL** when applicable (unless the user says to skip deploy). **Do not ask for permission** for pull, build, docker push, kubectl, clasp where still required. The user has authorized running commands needed for deploy.

### Full pipeline (run in order when deploying)

1. **`git pull --rebase`** (or `git pull`) in the repo(s) you are about to build/deploy — from WSL, correct `cd` to the Windows path under `/mnt/c/...`. If pull fails (conflicts), report and stop until resolved.
2. **Build** (npm / Docker) per sections below.
3. **`docker push`** the image(s) you built.
4. **`kubectl rollout restart`** + mandatory verification below.
5. **Legacy GAS:** **`clasp push`** from **`monitoring-app-v1/`** when any v1 source or **`monitoring-app-v1/.clasp.json`** changes.

Skip steps that do not apply (e.g. no GAS changes → no clasp). Never end with “you can run X” — **you run X**.

**After every image push + `kubectl rollout restart`, you must not stop at `rollout status` alone.** Continue until new pods are **Ready** and look healthy; if anything fails, **investigate and fix or report** (do not assume success).

### Mandatory post-rollout verification (run in the same WSL session)

1. `kubectl rollout status deployment/<name> -n leet-monitor --timeout=300s` (already part of the flow).
2. **`kubectl wait --for=condition=available deployment/<name> -n leet-monitor --timeout=180s`** — waits until the Deployment reports available (avoids `kubectl wait pod` errors when old pods are deleted during a rolling update).
3. **`kubectl get pods -n leet-monitor -l <app label> -o wide`** — confirm each replica is `READY` `1/1`, `STATUS` `Running`, ages match the rollout.

Do **not** rely on `kubectl wait pod -l ...` alone during rollouts; Kubernetes can remove a pod UID while `wait` still references it, which surfaces as `pods "…" not found` even though the rollout succeeded.

If **`rollout status` / deployment `available` wait fails**, or pods are **CrashLoopBackOff** / **ImagePullBackOff** / not `Running`:

- `kubectl describe pod -n leet-monitor <pod-name>` (events at the bottom).
- `kubectl logs -n leet-monitor <pod-name> --tail=120` (add `-c <container>` if multi-container).
- Fix the cause (manifest, image, secrets, probe, app error), rebuild/repush if needed, and **roll out again** with the same verification loop.

**Labels:** `monitoring-app-v2` → `-l app=monitoring-app-v2`. `people-analytics-api` → `-l app=people-analytics-api`. **`alert-app`** → `-l app=alert-app`.

